03886nmm a2200661Ia 9781479885886DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798858867 a10.18574/nyu/9781479885886.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547687  a(OCoLC)960871775  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS51.I9bG73 2016 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a939/.2322300aGraffiti from the Basilica in the Agora of Smyrna /ced. by Roger S. Bagnall, Roberta Casagrande-Kim, Akin Ersoy, Cumhur Tanriver. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aISAW Monographs ;v10 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn in-depth archaeological reportfeaturing graffiti found during a recent excavation at the Ancient Greek cityof Smyrna. The graffiti published in this richly-illustrated volume were discovered during an excavation of the Roman basilica in the Ancient Greek city of Smyrna, known today as Izmir, which is situated on the Aegean coast of modern Turkey. The project, which began in 2003, has unearthed a multitude of graffiti and drawings encompassing a wide range of subjects and interests, including local politics, nautical vessels, sex, and wordplay. Each graffito artifact holds the potential for vast historical and cultural data, rescued in this volume from the passage of time and razing ambitions of urban development. Given the city’s history, the potential wealth of knowledge to be gleamed from these discoveries is substantial: Smyrna has an uninterrupted history of settlement since the Neolithic–Copper ages, and remains today a major city and Mediterranean seaport at the crossroads of key trade routes. The present volume provides comprehensive editions of the texts, descriptions of the drawings, and an extensive introduction to the subjects of the graffiti, how they were produced, and who was responsible for them. A complete set of color photographs is included.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zTurkeyzİzmir. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zTurkeyzİzmir. 0aGraffitizTurkeyzİzmir. 0aGraffitizTurkeyzİzmir. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aBagnall, Roger S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCasagrande-Kim, Roberta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErsoy, Akin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTanriver, Cumhur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYolaçan, Burak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479885886.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479885886423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479885886/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles